I screened Vertigo for a big group of friends and this thing, I kid you not, put every single one of ‚Äòem to sleep. Out cold. And I know what you‚Äôre gonna say: ‚ÄúC-dog, you need to get yourself some new friends,‚Äù and you‚Äôre probably right, but you know what? I gotta say, this film isn‚Äôt as accessible as I remember. Look, I love Vertigo. People like us all do. There‚Äôs just something about the way it feels that really gets our motors purring. That rich VistaVision. Herrmann‚Äôs sumptuous score (in my opinion, the greatest achievement of his brilliant career). Stewart‚Äôs uncharacteristically demented performance. The haunting, dreamlike spell that permeates nearly every frame. The film is a technical wonder, practically unrivalled. We all know this. But when was the last time you watched Sight & Sound‚Äôs Greatest Film of All Time¬Æ with a bunch of normies? I‚Äôm not talking about some arthouse retrospective with like-minded cinephiles, or an in-the-mood, masturbatory solo viewing, I mean normal people, that is to say, people who couldn‚Äôt give two shits about dolly zooms, mise-en-scene, or idealogical editing. Watching this with the pressure of a casual audience, trying to defend the film‚Äôs goofier aspects, is an exhausting experience, let me tell you. The abominable way women are treated, that ridiculous stepping stool scene, the awkward blocking of Stewart‚Äôs hilariously inept shadowing, the abundance of lousy rear projection, the pathetic suicide attempt into the bay, Midge‚Äôs lopsided arc (which could‚Äôve been tidily wrapped up if it had been her at the tower instead of some random nun), all the way through to that (and I‚Äôm sorry to have to put it this way, but) just-plain-stupid final scene. Go ahead. Skip ahead to that final minute and look me in the eyes and tell me that works for you. Honestly,¬†I was kinda glad no one else was awake to see it!¬† And speaking of honesty, can we all just admit that it never quite plunges into the dark psychological depths its champions proclaim? Hitch is painting with pretty broad strokes as far as actual medical science is concerned. Sure, there are some interesting themes dealing with possession, guilt, lust, artificiality, etc., and you could analyze them to high hell (as every armchair-psychologist film critic has), but beyond the masterful way these elements are utilized to craft beautifully-staged cinematic sequences, I don‚Äôt think you‚Äôll find a chapter dedicated to Vertigo in any clinical texts. Anyway, I guess what it all boils down to is this: the next time I host a Hitchcock screening, we‚Äôre watching The Birds. It may not be Hitch‚Äôs finest hour, but it sure as hell won‚Äôt put ‚Äòem all to sleep.
